  "prompt": "Why does a salt solution conduct electricity?",
  "response": "A salt solution conducts electricity because the salt (sodium chloride, for example) dissociates into its constituent ions (sodium cations and chloride anions) when dissolved in water. These ions are charged particles that are free to move within the solution. \n\nWhen an electric potential is applied across the solution, the positive sodium ions (Na+) are attracted to the negative electrode, and the negative chloride ions (Cl-) are attracted to the positive electrode. This movement of ions constitutes an electric current, allowing the solution to conduct electricity.\n\nThe ability of a salt solution to conduct electricity depends on several factors, including the concentration of the salt, the type of salt, and the temperature of the solution. Higher concentrations of salt, certain types of salts that dissociate more completely, and higher temperatures all contribute to increased conductivity.",
